<div class="section" id="intro">
<h1><i class="fas fa-radiation"></i> Chernobyl: Reaction & Reform</h1>
<p>On April 26, 1986, Reactor 4 at the <strong>Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant</strong> exploded in Ukraine. Its RBMK Soviet design had serious safety flaws. Radiation spread across Europe, forcing the evacuation of Pripyat. The Soviet Union initially tried to hide the disaster, showing how politics can worsen crises (“Report on the Accident at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Station”).</p>
<p><strong>Thesis:</strong> Chernobyl caused worldwide fear, sparked immediate reactions, and led to reforms in nuclear safety, policy, and technology, showing how disasters can drive global change.</p>
</div>

<div class="section" id="history">
<h2><i class="fas fa-history"></i> History & Cover-Up</h2>
<p>The explosion happened during a poorly planned safety test. Human error and faulty reactor design caused overheating. Radiation was detected in Sweden before the Soviet Union admitted the accident. This exposed flaws in Soviet politics and prompted global concern (“Chernobyl Explosion”).</p>
<p>Earlier, the 1979 <strong>Three Mile Island</strong> accident in the U.S. showed the need for better emergency planning, but Chernobyl forced worldwide action (“Report on the Accident at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Station”).</p>
<img src="images/chernobyl_shelter.png" alt="Chernobyl Shelter">
</div>

<div class="section" id="safety">
<h2><i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i> Safety Improvements Over Time</h2>
<h3>After Chernobyl</h3>
<ul>
<li>RBMK reactors redesigned to prevent overheating (“RBMK Reactors – Appendix”).</li>
<li>IAEA strengthened safety rules worldwide (“How Chernobyl Jump-Started the Global Nuclear Safety Regime”).</li>
</ul>
<h3>After Fukushima, Japan (2011)</h3>
<ul>
<li>Backup cooling systems improved.</li>
<li>Stronger sea walls and flood protection added.</li>
<li>Automatic shutdown systems became mandatory.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Modern Designs</h3>
<p><strong>China:</strong> Hualong One reactors with double containment and passive cooling (“Plans For New Reactors Worldwide”).</p>
<p><strong>France:</strong> European Pressurized Reactors (Generation III+) with automatic shutdown systems. Modern reactors are safer and more efficient than older designs.</p>
</div>

<div class="section" id="nuclear-power">
<h2><i class="fas fa-atom"></i> Nuclear Power Worldwide</h2>
<p>Countries like France, China, and the U.S. rely on nuclear power. Nuclear energy grew from the 1970s, slowed after Chernobyl, and increased again after 2000.</p>

<h3>Map of Nuclear Plants</h3>
<iframe src="https://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/current-and-future-generation/plans-for-new-reactors-worldwide.aspx"></iframe>

